<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Albania</TITLE>
<H2>ALBANIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Located in southeastern Europe, the Balkan country of Albania gained its independence 
from the Ottoman Empire in 1912. Its struggle for independence, however, resulted in the  loss of 
about half its territory and 40 percent of its citizenry to neighboring Greece and Yugoslavia. During 
World War I, Albania became a battlefield in which much of the country was destroyed. Following 
the war, Albania was an independent state ruled by a monarchy. Although King Zog sought 
economic self-sufficiency, Albania became increasingly dependent on Italy. In 1939, Benito 
Mussolini occupied parts of Albania. The Albanian Communist Party was formed in 1941, and after 
World War II Albania became one of the world's most oppressive communist states. The 
communist regime was deposed in 1991, and current President Sali Berisha was elected in 1992.  
President Berisha is trying to implement an ambitious program of free market reforms. He has, 
however, encountered some political opposition, losing in November 1994 a referendum on his 
proposed constitution.
<P> <IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism)</I> <BR>
Most of Albania's tariffs range from 5 percent to 30 percent. Tariffs range from zero 
percent on heavy machinery used in agriculture, to 5 percent on mineral fuels, to 30 
percent on electronic equipment, to 20 percent on precision equipment, like oscilloscopes. 
Thus,  Albania's average tariff rate is probably between 15 percent and 20 percent. There 
are no import licenses required.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation:  2-Stable (Low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR> 
Final Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (Moderate tax rates)</I> <BR></B>
Albania has a top income tax rate of 24 percent. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT> Albania's top corporate tax rate is 30 percent. It also has a small business tax, a social contributions tax, and a turnover tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of government consumption)</I><BR>
The public sector generates about 66 percent of the GDP. <FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>   
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Inflation in Albania has been very high. The annual inflation rate was between 200 percent 
and 300 percent in 1992 and 1993. The government is currently implementing a tight 
monetary policy to curb high inflation rates.
<P><B>Factor #5:  Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Albania has quickly moved to open its borders to desperately needed foreign capital. It has 
passed laws forbidding state expropriation of foreign property. Foreign firms and domestic 
firms are treated equally under Albanian law. There are no sectors closed to foreign 
investment.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
While Albania has made significant strides in replacing the communist central bank and 
providing the avenues for a competitive market-driven system, Albania's financial system is 
still not fully private. Albania's financial system consists of seven major banks. Of these, 
four are state-owned, two are joint ventures between state-owned banks and private banks, 
and only one is fully private. There are few governmental restrictions on foreign banks.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Albania has a minimum wage. Most prices are controlled by the huge, state-owned sector 
of the economy which still receives government subsidies. These enterprises are often able 
to control prices because they can undercut prices determined by the market.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
While the government has made great strides in privatization, the private sector is still small 
when compared to the size of public holdings. In addition, Albania's court system is still too 
immature to handle a growing case load of property disputes. Thus, the biggest threat to 
private property remains that large state-owned sector and an inadequate legal system.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Albania has made some progress in streamlining its bureaucracy. Nevertheless,  the 
bureaucracy has been unable to adapt to the emerging private sector. It is still too large and 
inefficient.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
While Albania's legal market may be growing, many consumers and entrepreneurs still find 
it easier and more profitable to deal in the black market. Taxi and bus transportation still is 
provided by black marketeers. Smugglers find that the scarcities caused by high tariffs on 
auto parts provide them with ample opportunities for profit on the black market.
 <P><B>Summary</B>
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.55</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 4 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1] Information to determine the tax on the average income level was not available.<BR>
[2] Budgetary figures are not available for Albania. Thus, generating a government consumption figure is not possible. Albania was graded strictly on the basis that the public sector generates 65.3 percent of gross domestic product.</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
