<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Austria</TITLE>
<H2>AUSTRIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Austria has long played an important role in European history and culture. Following World 
War I,  Austria's government intervened deeply in the economy, causing massive economic 
recession in the 1930s. At the end of World War II, it was occupied by both U.S. and Soviet 
troops. But in 1955, Austria was freed from occupying armies and became a completely 
independent and neutral country. Although Austria has been ruled by mainly socialist parties since 
then, it has pursued some very free market policies. This has helped Austria maintain a relatively 
high standard of living.
<P><IMG SRC="austria.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Austria has an average tariff rate of 2 percent to 3 percent. However, some tariffs on specific 
products like agricultural goods can be quite high. In addition, Austria limits agricultural 
imports according to a quota system. Still, as a new member of the European Union, trade 
barriers are expected to fall.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5+ (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4.5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Austria has a top income tax rate of 50 percent. The average income level is taxed at a rate of 
32 percent. Austria has a top corporate tax rate of 34 percent. However, Austria has a 34 
percent capital gains tax, a 20 percent value-added tax, and a 3.5 percent real estate tax, 
among many other taxes.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Austria's government consumes 18 percent of GDP. Austria has a large state-owned industrial 
sector.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low levels of inflation) </I><BR>
Austria had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 3.6 percent. This increased 
to 4.4 percent in 1992.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Austria is very dependent on foreign investment and welcomes it openly. Few restrictions exist. 
However, foreign investors must sometimes deal with slow bureaucratic procedures to gain 
approval for new operations.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Foreign banks can operate in Austria so long as they have prior government approval. Austrian 
banks are permitted to engage in all kinds of services, including the underwriting of loans 
and the brokering of securities and mutual funds. They also may own subsidiaries that 
underwrite and sell insurance policies. Austrian banks are also allowed to invest in, develop, 
and manage real estate ventures.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most wages and prices are set by the market. However, Austrian businesses voluntarily 
cooperate with the government to set prices. Thus, prices in Austria are not completely 
free. Austria maintains a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property is very secure in Austria, which has an efficient and well established legal system that 
respects and protects private property and contractual agreements.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Although Austria experienced long periods of economic growth after World War II, it allowed 
the state to become involved in regulating the economy. There is a growing environmental 
movement that threatens to shackle many Austrian businesses with burdensome 
regulations. Moreover, workers in Austria are pampered and coddled by the state, hindering 
the competitiveness of business even further. Nevertheless, by global standards Austria's 
economy is only moderately regulated.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
The black market is relatively small to non-existent in Austria. Goods and services move fairly 
freely across the border, limiting the incentives for smuggling.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.05</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 1  
Taxation 4.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 1  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
