<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>The Bahamas</TITLE>
<H2>THE BAHAMAS</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	An archipelago some 50 miles east of Florida, the Bahamas consists of some 700 islands, 
only 30 of which are inhabited. The Bahamas is a parliamentary democracy and a member of the 
British Commonwealth. Its biggest industry is tourism and, with a few notable exceptions, the 
economy is essentially free from government controls.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
A main source of revenue for the Bahamian government is import duties. Its tariff rates are 
very high. The general rate of duty charges on imports is 33 percent. The Bahamas 
maintains no other significant barriers. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT> 
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 1-Stable (Very low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 1-Stable (Very low tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 1-Stable (Very low tax rates)</I><BR>
The Bahamas is a tax haven. There is no income tax or corporate income tax in the Bahamas. 
There is no capital gains tax or value-added tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
The Bahamian government plays a limited role in the economy. Government consumption as a 
percentage of GDP is 12 percent, which is low. <FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT> 
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of inflation)</I><BR>
The Bahamas historically has had low levels of inflation. From 1980 to 1991, its average annual 
inflation rate was 5.9 percent. Today it is about 3.3 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
There remain significant barriers to foreign investment in the Bahamas. For example, the 
government restricts foreign investment in areas that directly compete with Bahamian-
owned businesses, such as construction. It does this by preventing foreign companies from 
obtaining business licenses and by imposing other requirements in areas where Bahamian 
businesses already exist. Further, there is no foreign investment code in the Bahamas.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
The Bahamas is one of the financial centers of the Caribbean. Its financial sector is extremely 
open to foreigners. The Bahamas seeks to attract foreign banks.  
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
The Bahamas maintains some price controls on such items as automobiles, auto parts, flour, 
gasoline, public transportation, and utilities, but its wages are mainly determined by the 
market. There is now no minimum wage, although it will be introduced soon by the 
government.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Private property is easy to acquire and protect in the Bahamas. An advanced and efficient legal 
system based on English common law adequately protects private property.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low levels of government regulation) </I><BR>
Regulation is virtually non-existent in the Bahamas. The government follows a hands-off 
approach to business. Opening a business in the Bahamas is simple. There are no specific 
requirements for establishing a business and English common law is used to enforce 
contracts. Profits are not taxed and businesses are free from burdensome regulations.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
The black market in the Bahamas is like those in most developed countries: restricted to guns 
and drugs. Gambling is legalized in the Bahamas. Since the government outlaws few things 
and businesses are free to operate as they see fit, the black market is very small. Still, high 
trade barriers result in some smuggling in such items as auto parts and electronics.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.10</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 2  
Taxation 1			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 1  
Foreign Investment 4		Black Market 2  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>

<P>[1 ] It is impossible to generate an average tariff rate for the Bahamas because information on tax 
revenues generated from imports is not available. However, the Bahamas' general tariff rate of 33 percent, 
which applies to most imports, was used. Other tariff rates range from zero percent on foodstuffs to 47 
percent on luxury items to a top rate of 200 percent. Still, since most imports fall into the general 
category, the 33 percent figure most closely represents the Bahamas' average tariff rate. For more 
information, see The Bahamas, International Tax and Business Guide, 1994 edition, Deloitte Touche 
Tohmatsu International, New York, New York, 1994.<BR>
[2 ] This information was generated by using central government consumption as a percentage of GDP. 
This figure is for 1987, the most recent year available, and was generated from statistics found in World 
Tables 1994,  The World Bank, Washington, D.C., 1994.
</FONT>
