<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Bahrain</TITLE>
<H2>BAHRAIN</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Bahrain declared its independence from the United Kingdom in 1971 and became a 
member of the United Nations and the Arab League in the same year. Bahrain has also maintained 
a free market system. Oil is the main export product of the country. With oil reserves expected to 
last only through the turn of the century, the government is pursuing ways to transform Bahrain into 
an industrialized country. 
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Bahrain has few barriers to trade. It has an average tariff rate of about 3.3 percent. However, it 
maintains non-tariff barriers through strict labeling requirements on imported products. This 
often poses a barrier to imports because exporters do not wish to spend the extra money to 
meet the requirements.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 1-Stable (Very low tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 1-Stable (Very low tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 1-Stable (Very low tax rates) </I><BR>
Bahrain has no taxes on income or corporate profits. There is no capital gains tax or value-
added tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Bahrain has a high government consumption rate of 28.8 percent of the GDP.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1- (Very low inflation rate) </I><BR>
Prices in Bahrain are dropping . The average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was a 
minus 0.3 percent. Today it is about the same.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR> 
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Bahrain maintains few barriers to foreign investment and maintains no foreign investment law. 
Instead, it relies on various commercial codes to govern foreign investment. For example, 
there are no ownership requirements on new industrial investments. Foreigners cannot own 
more than 49 percent of non-industrial enterprises. Moreover, foreigners are not permitted 
to purchase and own land.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Bahrain has a vibrant and competitive banking market. Banks in Bahrain face few government 
restrictions. The government has made the process of establishing a bank in Bahrain easy 
by streamlining the paperwork process and placing few, if any, restrictions and 
requirements on new banks. Foreign banks are welcome. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Most wages and prices in Bahrain are set by the market. Price controls remain only on some 
basic foodstuffs and petroleum products. Bahrain has a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property is secure in Bahrain. Expropriation in Bahrain remains unlikely. The court system 
protecting private property is efficient.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of regulation) </I><BR>
Bahrain has an efficient and unobtrusive bureaucracy that poses no significant threat to 
business. Businesses are free to operate as they see fit. Opening a business is 
straightforward. 
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Bahrain has a limited black market. Since it has virtually no barriers to imports, smuggling is not 
a problem. 
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
<P>
<P>
























 <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 1.80</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 2  
Taxation 1			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 1  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 1  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
