<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Belarus</TITLE>
<H2>BELARUS</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Lying between Poland and Russia, Belarus has one of the highest income levels in the 
former Soviet Union. The economy is heavily industrialized. However, the collapse of the Soviet 
Union has left the economy in shambles. Market reforms have been half-hearted, and recent trends 
suggest a retrenchment of old socialist economic policies. As a result, the size of the economy has 
shrunk. 
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><H3> Factor #1: Trade Policy</H3>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Belarus maintains relatively high barriers to trade. Its average tariff rate is 12.5 percent.<FONT 
SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   It maintains non-tariff barriers through heavy user fees on 
imports and some currency requirements on businesses trying to import raw materials.
<P><H3> Factor #2: Taxation</H3>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates) <BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4.5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Belarus's income taxes are among the highest in Europe. Its top income tax rate is 60 percent. 
Belarus has a top corporate income tax of 30 percent, but it can be as high as 80 percent on 
income earned in auctions and through leases. Belarus also maintains a value-added tax of 
10 percent. 
<P><H3> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</H3>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption) </I><BR>
The government is very active in the economy. In fact, most enterprises are still government-
owned. Belarus's government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 19 percent.
<P><H3> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</H3>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high inflation rate) </I><BR>
Belarus has chronically high inflation rates. In 1992 inflation rose over 1,000 percent. 
<P><H3> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</H3>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Foreign investment in Belarus is hindered by an insufficient legal system. A lack of contractual 
protection from the courts is one example. Nevertheless, Belarus recently opened its 
economy to some direct foreign investment.
<P><H3> Factor #6: Banking</H3>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
The banking system in Belarus is controlled by the government. Most banks are owned and 
operated by the government. However, recently Belarus has eased some regulations on 
commercial banking, freeing banks from government oversight. Now banks are more free 
from government oversight and in setting internal banking policies. However, the 
government still controls or owns most banks. 
<P><H3> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</H3>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate levels of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Belarus has a very high minimum wage. While many prices and wages in Belarus are free of 
government control, some price controls remain on such items as some forms of energy 
and various foodstuffs.
<P><H3> Factor #8: Property Rights</H3>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection for private property) </I><BR>
Property is at risk in Belarus. Belarus's legal system does not fully protect private property. 
The primary problem is that contracts are not always enforced by the inefficient court 
system. However, the framework for protecting private property is being established.
<P><H3> Factor #9: Regulation</H3>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
The government of Belarus imposes significant regulations on businesses. Corruption exists and 
regulations are not always evenly applied.
<P><H3> Factor #10: Black Market</H3>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Belarus has a huge black market. Mainly left over from the former Soviet Union, the black 
market has actually increased in size because of slow economic reforms.
<P><H3>Summary</H3>
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.85</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 4.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 5  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
 <P>[1]  Based on taxes raised from international trade taken as a percentage of imports in 1992.
</FONT>
