<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Belize</TITLE>
<H2>BELIZE</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Located just south of Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula, the Central American country of Belize 
is among the fastest growing countries in the region. Belize's economy stagnated in the early 1980s 
because its main export, sugar cane, was hit by disease. Since then, however, Belize has had 
extremely high rates of economic growth because of the sound economic policies and favorable 
economic conditions in Mexico and North America, to which many of its goods are exported.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Trade is a main source of government revenue in Belize. Tariffs are very high and average 21.5 
percent. Belize requires import licenses for 26 different products. A special stamp duty of 
12 percent is added to various products.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation:  4-Stable (High tax rate)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rate)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rate)</I><BR>
Taxes in Belize are high, with a top marginal income tax rate of 45 percent. The average 
income level is taxed at 15 percent. Belize has a flat corporate income tax rate of  35 
percent. It also has a social contributions tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
The government consumes 19.3 percent of GDP.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low inflation rate)</I><BR>
The average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 2.9 percent. No reliable information 
was available for later years. 
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Foreign investment is not permitted in a variety of industries and economic activities, including 
accounting, beekeeping, commercial fishing, merchandising and distribution,  sugar cane 
production, and transportation. However, Belize offers tax holidays, which eliminate taxes 
on investments for a specified period, to investments in many other areas. This encourages 
investments that result in increased exports and more jobs.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Bank loans are closely regulated. Banks in Belize are under tight government control. 
Foreigners need to acquire permission from the government to operate in Belize. Foreigners 
are discouraged by such government interference. Competition among banks is limited 
because new bank formation is hindered by government restrictions. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Most wages and prices are set by the market. However, price controls exist on foodstuffs. 
Belize maintains a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (High level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Belize is pursuing an ambitious privatization program that is adding more private property to the 
economy. The chances for expropriation remain remote and there is an adequate court 
system in place.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of regulation)</I><BR>
Regulations are onerous in Belize's economy. Regulations are often applied haphazardly. 
Existing regulations pose a substantial burden on business. Obtaining a business license can 
be complicated.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Black market activity in Belize takes many forms. Some construction, transportation, and other 
"cash" transactions are done primarily in the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 <P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.70</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
