<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Brazil</TITLE>
<H2>BRAZIL</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Brazil is the largest country in South America. It was once a colony of Portugal. Under 
President Fernando Collor, who was impeached in 1992, Brazil reduced trade barriers, privatized 
state-owned enterprises, controlled inflation, and maintained a tight monetary policy. When the new 
president, Itamar Franco, assumed office, he stated that Collor's policies would be continued. 
However, this did not happen. Under Franco, Collor's reforms lost their momentum. While he 
continued privatization and reduced government spending, he also raised taxes and increased 
government control over credit. Brazil's new President, Fernando Henrique Cardoso, promises to 
reduce taxes and tariff rates, as well as privatize many state-owned businesses.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Brazil maintains an average tariff rate of 14.3 percent. It has other barriers to trade as well, 
such as import licenses and other duties. For example, imported personal computers are 
subject to a 35 percent duty, a 10 percent freight insurance charge, a 15 percent value-
added tax, and a 17 percent sales tax. These duties increase the price of imported 
computers by over 100 percent.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2+ (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3+ (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3+ (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR>
Brazil has a top income tax rate of 35 percent. The Brazilian government determines tax 
brackets based on what it calls a "fiscal unit of reference."  This is a method to determine 
an individual's annual income amount after a year's worth of inflation, which is very high 
in Brazil. With this method, the government gets the maximum amount of revenue from 
income that is continuously inflating. However, the average Brazilian does not pay taxes. 
Using the per capita GDP of $2,800 expressed in U.S. dollars, the average Brazilian 
taxpayer falls into the lowest tax bracket in which no taxes are owed. Brazil has a maximum 
corporate tax rate of 25 percent and a state corporate tax of 5 percent for a total top rate of 
30 percent. In addition, Brazil has a 25 percent capital gains tax, a top federal value-added 
tax of 365 percent, a 7 percent to 25 percent state value-added tax, a 10 percent social 
contributions tax, and a maximum municipal service tax of 10 percent.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Brazil's government consumes 14.7 percent of the country's GDP. The government is entering 
an ambitious program to privatize most state-owned businesses.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation)</I><BR>
From 1980 to 1991, the annual inflation rate was 327.6 percent. The annual inflation rate in 
1993 was over 2,500 percent.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Brazil still maintains barriers to foreign investment. Restrictions on investments in the service 
industries can be high. For example, foreign capital investments in petroleum, banking, 
insurance, telecommunications, and mining are limited. Other investments, such as in 
transportation, utilities, media, real estate, and shipping, are prohibited. Brazil also imposes 
local content requirements on foreign equity participation.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Of the few foreign banks that exist in Brazil, all are restricted from expanding branches or doing 
business with state-owned companies. Brazilian law prohibits new foreign participants in 
the capital stock of national trading banks as well as any increase in equity participation in 
Brazilian banks. Moreover, Brazil has not permitted the entrance of any new banks. 
Indications are that this policy will continue. Domestic banks are allowed to engage in 
securities exchanges and insurance services, but they are prevented from engaging in real 
estate ventures and most equity investments.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Brazil has had a long history of wage and price controls. Brazil last froze prices in 1990, but 
controls have been gradually eased since that time. Nevertheless, Brazil still maintains price 
controls on a variety of goods and services such as some foodstuffs. Businesses may be 
required to ask permission from the government to increase prices, even if production costs 
rise. Many companies are not free to set their own prices. Brazil maintains a minimum 
wage. 
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
There is little chance that the private property of foreign investors will be expropriated in Brazil. 
Because there are a number of major multinational corporations in the country and the 
government is trying to attract foreign investment, the protection of foreign-owned property 
is adequate. However, domestically owned property is at risk. 
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
Government regulation is rampant in Brazil. Its economy is heavily regulated. Environmental, 
health, consumer, labor, financial, and a host of other regulations greatly restrain business 
activities.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Brazil has a moderate level of black market activity. Brazil's black market has shrunk, 
however, in recent years as Brazil has reduced trade barriers on previously protected 
goods, reducing the ability of smugglers to make a profit on highly taxed products.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 <P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.30</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
