<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>People's Republic of China</TITLE>
<H2>PEOPLE'S REPUBLIC OF CHINA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	While China is often criticized for its human rights abuses and its communist political 
system, China economically is more advanced and open than it was several decades ago. Many of 
the economic reforms of the 1980s were undone following the Tiananmen Square massacre in 
1989. However, since that time, China once again has pursued economic liberalization. These 
reforms have paid off as economic growth reached 12 percent in 1993. While China's economy is 
opening, an overwhelmingly large part of it remains under state control.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
China has an average tariff rate of about 30 percent. It uses numerous non-tariff barriers to 
deter imports. These barriers include licensing requirements, trade quotas, and local content 
restrictions. China signed a trade agreement in 1992 with the U.S. to reduce trade 
restrictions by 1997. China is applying for membership in the General Agreement on Tariffs 
and Trade, which has forced it to take some steps toward freer trade.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
China's taxes are high. China has a top marginal income tax rate of 45 percent. The tax on the 
average income level is 15 percent. China has a top corporate tax level of 30 percent. Yet 
China also has a 33 percent capital gains tax, a 17 percent value-added tax, and a business 
tax ranging from 3 percent to 20 percent.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of government consumption)</I><BR>
As a communist system, most property is owned by the state. The World Bank reports that 
China's government consumes only 9.8 percent of the GDP, which is up from 8.3 percent 
in 1980. Still, China's state-owned sector contributes almost all GDP. By definition, 
therefore, China's government consumption is very high due to the fact that the state owns 
most of the economy.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of inflation)</I><BR>
Being a command economy, China had an average annual rate of inflation of only 5.8 percent 
from 1980 to 1991. Inflation was 8.1 percent in 1992. However, this underestimates the 
real rate of inflation because the communist government controls prices.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
China's government has always maintained barriers against foreign investment. China suffers 
from a lack of foreign investment codes. Moreover, the Chinese use their foreign 
investment policy to prevent foreign investments in industries owned by the government. 
However, China's special foreign investment zones in the south give it a somewhat better 
score.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
China liberalized its banking industry in 1988 and allowed the creation of domestic and foreign-
owned banks. However, the government tries to prevent foreign banks from operating in 
China. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate wage and price controls)</I><BR>
China has a history of price controls. After the 1993 recession, China imposed price controls on 
such items as foodstuffs and utilities. China has a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (Low level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
China is a communist system in which most of the property remains in government hands. 
However,  China is currently privatizing some major industries, thus moving state-owned 
assets into private hands. Still, private property has yet to become common in the Chinese 
system. 
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
In an attempt to boost the private sector, the Chinese bureaucracy sometimes does not enforce 
cumbersome regulations. China still has a state planning agency that makes significant 
business and economic decisions. This central planning results in high levels of regulation.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Because of existing trade restrictions and communist economic planning, China has a rather 
large black market. Smuggling in consumer electronics like TVs and video cassette 
recorders is quite high. Black market activity in basic staples is abundant.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.80</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 5 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
