<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Colombia</TITLE>
<H2>COLOMBIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Colombia's political system has come under much pressure in recent years because of the 
drug trade. However, recent economic reforms have made the economy one of the most stable in 
the region. Colombia's economy remains healthy with some of the highest growth rates in South 
America. While growth has slowed recently, it still averaged 3.3 percent from 1989 to 1993. 
However, Colombia's newly elected President Ernesto Samper has called for increased government 
spending on social welfare programs that could jeopardize recent economic gains.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Colombia has an average tariff rate of 10 percent, down from 35.5 percent in 1990. Colombia 
maintains many non-tariff barriers. For example, it requires importers to gain licenses for 
automobile, dairy, poultry, and other products. 
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 4- (High tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation:  3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
Colombia has an effective top income tax rate of 30 percent. 
<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   The average income level is taxed at a rate of less than 5 percent. Many 
of these taxpayers are not required to fill out a tax return. 
<FONT SIZE="-2">[2]</FONT>   The government is cracking down on tax fraud and more 
collections are being made than ever before. Colombia has a top corporate tax rate of 30 
percent. In addition, Colombia has a 30 percent capital gains tax and a 14 percent value-
added tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of government consumption in the 
economy)</I><BR>
Even with Colombia's costly war on drugs, its government has managed to reduce its role in the 
economy. Colombia's government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 10.4 percent.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High inflation rate)</I><BR>
Colombia had an average inflation rate of 25 percent from 1980 to 1991. Since then, the 
inflation rate has remained stable at around 22 percent to 25 percent.

<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Colombia permits 100 percent foreign ownership in almost all sectors of its economy. The few 
exceptions are in national security and hazardous waste industries. Permission for 
investments is needed only for the public service, water, waste, and transportation 
industries, or for large investments in mining and petroleum enterprises. A simple 
registration and licensing process is required for all investments.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
During the 1980s, the government nationalized the banks. However, it now is selling them back 
to the private sector. Still, Colombia has yet to achieve a completely free banking system. 
Domestic banks may engage in selling securities, insurance policies, and investment  
services. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Colombia has one of the most free market pricing policies in Latin America. Almost all prices 
are set by the market. The only exceptions are on a few agricultural and petroleum 
products. However, Colombia maintains a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate protection of private property)</I><BR>
The biggest threat to private property in Colombia is the violence created by the drug cartels 
and the government's attempt to distribute wealth more equally. Private property is 
generally well protected in Colombia. The government is privatizing the state-owned 
enterprises. However, Colombia is also in the midst of a major agrarian reform program 
which may result in the expropriation of private land.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of regulation)</I><BR>
Colombia is a free market economy and the government tends to exercise minimal control of 
the private sector. Obtaining a business license in Colombia is not difficult. There is a 
limited registration process. Moreover, the Colombian government tends to allow 
businesses to operate as they see fit. There are very few burdensome regulations on 
business.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high black market activity)</I><BR>
The drug trade makes Colombia's black market rather large. Moreover, as much as 43 percent 
of the labor in Bogota is supplied on the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.90</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 2  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 4		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Colombia's top marginal income tax rate is actually 55 percent. This rate is composed of a top 
tax rate of 30 percent, plus a 25 percent tax penalty for making over a specific income. However, the 25 
percent becomes a deduction on the following year's taxes. Thus, for the purposes of grading this factor, 
only the top rate of 30 percent was used.<BR>
 [2] For the purposes of grading, the 5 percent figure was used.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
