<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Costa Rica</TITLE>
<H2>COSTA RICA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Central American country of Costa Rica declared its independence from Spain in 
1821. The U.S. remains Costa Rica's largest trading partner. Foreign aid has drastically decreased 
since the end of the Cold War and trade between the U.S. and Costa Rica is growing. Costa Rica's 
economic growth is mainly the result of increased trade and economic reforms.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Although Costa Rica has been moving to open its borders, it still remains a rather difficult 
market to penetrate. Costa Rica has an average tariff rate of 12.7 percent. Costa Rica's 
customs procedures are cumbersome and plagued with inefficiencies. Many importers are 
forced to hire a customs specialist just to get their products across the borders. Costa Rica 
maintains significant non-tariff barriers. For example, import permits are required for dairy 
products, pork, poultry, meat, rice, beans, potatoes, onions, and wheat.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR>
Costa Rica has a top marginal income tax rate of 25 percent. The tax on the average income is 
about 15 percent. Costa Rica has a top corporate income tax rate of 30 percent. Costa Rica 
has a 10 percent sales tax.
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Costa Rica's government consumption as a percentage of GDP is about 15.8 percent, down 
from 18.2 percent in 1980.
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of inflation)</I><BR>
Costa Rica had an inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 22.9 percent. The rate for 1992 was 21 
percent.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Costa Rica offers one of the best investment climates in Central America. Costa Rica has no 
repatriation requirements, allowing foreigners to take out all of their profits, and a widening 
group of foreign investment incentives. Some tax holidays are offered for specific 
investments. Costa Rica does not discriminate against foreign investors, treating them no 
differently than local investors. Some restrictions remain on utilities and services, where 
investments are barred.
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Foreigners are prevented from engaging in some banking services like checking and savings. 
However, banking competition is generally free and open in Costa Rica. Banks are not 
permitted to engage in selling insurance policies and other services. 
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Most wages and prices are set by the market. As a condition for an International Monetary 
Fund loan, Costa Rica was forced to eliminate most of its price controls, except for those 
on a few basic foodstuffs. Costa Rica maintains a minimum wage.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-(Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Private property is not entirely safe in Costa Rica. Expropriation remains a threat.  When 
property is expropriated, rarely is the market value provided to the property owner. In 
many cases, the government offers no compensation. Some U.S. property rights claims 
date back 25 years. Domestic property owners could lose their land to increasing numbers 
of squatters who band together to expropriate property. Their actions are becoming 
increasingly violent. The legal system has been unable to deal with the situation.
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate levels of regulation)</I><BR>
There are few major barriers to opening a business in Costa Rica. Regulations are easily 
understood and for the most part are equally applied. There is scant evidence of corruption 
or bribery. However, some regulations pose a moderate threat to businesses, such as 
environmental impact studies. Moreover, the government requires private companies to 
grant vacations, holidays, overtime, and social insurance.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
The black market is moderate in Costa Rica. Some construction, telephone installation, and 
transportation is performed in the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.90</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 3  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 4		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
