<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>The Czech Republic</TITLE>
<H2>THE CZECH REPUBLIC</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Czech Republic became an independent state in January 1993 after its separation from 
Slovakia. Since the breakup of the former Soviet Union, the Czech Republic has pursued economic 
liberalization. It trades mainly with the former communist countries of the Soviet Union and with the 
European Union. At least half of its foreign trade is with countries in the European Union, mainly Germany. 
Trade with other Eastern and Central European countries has fallen to about 20 percent since 1990. Leading 
exports include automobiles, heavy machinery, and steel. Leading imports are automobiles, chemicals, 
finished engineering products, and foodstuffs. The Czech Republic is one of the leading free market 
reformers from the group of former communist states.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">

<P><B> Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of protectionism)</I><BR>
The Czech Republic is one of the most open markets in Europe. While the Czech Republic has an 
average tariff rate of about 4.5 percent, it still maintains tariffs as high as 70 percent on some 
products. However, there are no other significant barriers to imports.
<P><B> Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
The Czech Republic has high taxes, with a top marginal income tax rate of 44 percent. The tax on the 
average income level, however, is zero percent. The Czech Republic has a top marginal corporate 
income tax rate of 42 percent. It also has a 42 percent capital gains tax, a 23 percent value-added 
tax, and a real estate transfer tax. 
<P><B> Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
The Czech Republic has one of the freest economies of former communist states. Its government 
consumption as a percentage of GDP was 26 percent in 1991.<FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT> 
<P><B> Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate inflation rate)</I><BR>
The Czech Republic has pursued an anti-inflationary monetary policy since 1992. The inflation rate in 
1992 was 10 percent, and in 1993 it was 18 percent. This amounts to an average of 14 percent for 
1992-1993. Inflation is expected to be about 12 percent in 1994.
<P><B> Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
All sectors of the Czech Republic are open to foreign investment except defense-related industries. 
<P><B> Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
Competition in the Czech banking system is increasing. There are few, if any, barriers to opening either 
a foreign or domestic bank. Banks in the Czech Republic are open to foreign participation. A 
foreign bank can establish a wholly owned bank, buy into an existing bank, or open a branch. 
Private Czech banks can engage in selling securities and making some investments.
<P><B> Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Most wages and prices are set by the market. However, price controls remain in effect for many 
utilities. The Czech Republic maintains minimum wage standards.
<P><B> Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Private property receives a high level of protection in the Czech Republic. The chances of expropriation 
are highly unlikely. However, a system of law in which property receives total protection has yet to 
be formed. 
<P><B> Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of regulation)</I><BR>
The Czech Republic has few regulations on businesses. Most companies do not require a license to 
open their doors for business. The Czech Republic has plans to further reduce regulations on 
businesses.
<P><B> Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
The black market is of moderate size in the Czech Republic. Some goods and services are still supplied 
on the black market.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.10</TH>  
    
Trade 1				Banking 1  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 2 
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 1  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3 
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This is the most recent figure available and probably has dropped since 1991.

</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
