<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Dominican Republic</TITLE>
<H2>DOMINICAN REPUBLIC</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Dominican Republic won its independence from Spain in 1865. Since independence, 
this Caribbean island nation has developed a large agricultural industry. The government has 
intervened quite often in this and other industries. In the 1980s the country suffered a major 
economic crisis as its socialist economic policies and bad weather ruined agricultural production. 
Since 1990, the government has been trying to reform the economy, but not much progress has 
been made.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
The Dominican Republic maintains very high trade barriers. Its average tariff rate is about 27 
percent. Non-tariff barriers include a consumption tax which ranges from 5 percent to 80 
percent; in some cases that tax raises prices so high that some products become 
unaffordable and therefore are effectively barred from the country. For example, a 
consumption tax is added to automobiles based on their engine size. As a result, imported 
cars are far out of reach of the average citizen. Import licenses exist for most products.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2+ (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3+ (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3+ (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR>
The Dominican Republic's marginal top income tax rate is 26 percent. This will be reduced to 
25 percent in 1995. People who make an average income pay no taxes. The top corporate 
tax rate is 26 percent in 1994, to be reduced to 25 percent in 1995. The Dominican 
Republic also has a 26 percent capital gains tax and an 8 percent value-added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
According to the World Bank, the Dominican Republic's government consumption as a 
percentage of GDP figure is 8.9 percent. However, this figure is highly understated because 
state-owned companies produce a majority of GDP. 
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of inflation)</I><BR>
The Dominican Republic had an annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 of 24.5 percent. 
Inflation fell to 4 percent in 1992.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Foreign investment is discouraged by government bureaucracy and corruption. Prohibitions on 
foreign investment exist in the following industries: communications, media, national 
defense, transportation, and public utilities. Foreigners need a presidential decree to permit 
ownership of more than one-half acre of land. The Dominican Republic maintains 
repatriation requirements and prevents the reinvestment of some profits. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Foreign banks are virtually shut out of the Dominican Republic. The two exceptions are 
Citibank and the Bank of Nova Scotia, which have been operating relatively freely in the 
Dominican Republic for decades. The government strictly controls the supply of credit. 
Foreign companies cannot obtain loans from local banks for a period longer than one year.  
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Most wages and prices are set by the market. The government combats inflation with sound 
monetary measures and price controls. The Dominican Republic has a minimum wage 
policy.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4- (Low level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Property rights are not respected and receive low levels of protection in the Dominican 
Republic. The court system is inefficient; corruption and bureaucratic red tape run high; 
and property can be expropriated by the government.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
Regulations are not applied evenly or honestly. Corruption and red tape pose significant burdens 
to businesses.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of black market activity)</I><BR>
The Dominican Republic has a high level of black market activity, particularly in labor services. 
Competition for workers is so intense that many legal labor regulations are ignored.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.40</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 4		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
