<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Egypt</TITLE>
<H2>EGYPT</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Egypt gained its independence from Britain in 1922. Today, Egypt is a social democracy 
ruled by President Hosni Mubarak. The government launched a desperately needed market 
liberalization program in 1991. It has attempted to remove the state from the market. However, 
very little progress has been made in privatizing Egypt's massive and inefficient public sector. Nor 
has much been done to reform and reduce the size of the bureaucracy. In the past two years 
Egypt's tourist industry has suffered a billion-dollar-a-year loss because of radical Islamic terrorist 
attacks on foreign tourists and government officials. Egypt is the second-largest annual recipient of 
U.S. foreign aid.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protection)</I><BR>
Egypt has made modest progress over the past several years in liberalizing its trade policy.  
Nevertheless, Egypt remains one of the most heavily protected markets in the world. 
Egypt's average tariff rate of around 30 percent is exceptionally high.  Such non-tariff 
import barriers as import bans also protect domestic industries. Some  trade reforms have 
been undertaken, including the 1993 reduction of the maximum tariff rate on most items 
from 100 percent to 80 percent and the elimination of import bans on most commodities. 
Nevertheless, 159 previously banned items have been placed on a "quality control" list.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)</I><BR>
Egypt has a top income tax rate of 65 percent. The tax on the average income level is 23 
percent. Corporate income is taxed at a rate of 40 percent. Egypt has a 40 percent capital 
gains tax and a wealth tax of 32 percent on income over a certain level. It also has a sales 
tax and a social insurance tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of government consumption)</I><BR>
A large and inefficient state sector accounts for 70 percent of industrial production. Egypt's 
government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 14.6 percent.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of inflation)</I><BR>
Egypt's average annual rate of inflation was 12.5 percent from 1980 to 1991. In 1992, the 
inflation rate rose to 19.5 percent. The estimate for 1993 is approximately 9 percent. 
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
The Egyptian government has established business zones free of customs duties, sales, and 
other taxes. Despite these improvements, Egypt's cumbersome bureaucracy continues to 
frustrate foreign investment. Foreign investors occasionally face official discrimination, 
particularly when their proposals threaten public sector interests. While foreign investors are 
allowed to buy most privatized enterprises, Egyptian bidders still receive an advantage in 
the bidding. In practice, 100 percent foreign ownership is rarely approved.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Egypt's banking industry is dominated by the public sector. The state-owned and central bank 
exercises considerable control over private banks. Egyptian banks have formed joint 
ventures with such companies as Barclays' and Bank of America. However, the 
government will not permit the establishment of new joint venture banks or branches. Joint 
venture banks are subject to strict control by the central bank, which determines the fees 
and commissions they can charge. The central bank also exercises control over the 
appointment of directors of joint venture banks and determines their interest rates for loans 
in the economy. The central bank also requires joint venture banks to deposit with it an 
amount of local currency for which they earn no interest.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Price controls have been removed on most products. Remaining price controls should be 
removed within the next year, except on pharmaceutical products. However, gasoline, 
flour, and sugar remain subsidized. The existence of a massive public sector limits the 
private sector's ability to set wages and prices. The government limits the amount of profit 
earned on some imported goods. There is a minimum wage. 
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Egypt's commendable privatization effort is bogged down.  While private property is protected 
by the constitution, the Egyptian judiciary is inefficient. 
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
Corruption is endemic in the Egyptian bureaucracy, which is massive and inefficient. Bribery is 
the norm.  The business environment is overregulated, and investors have difficulty 
obtaining permits for imports. 
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
With its long commitment to a command economy and the slowness of its economic reforms, 
Egypt retains a large black market sector. While most goods are available in shops, the 
substantial trade restrictions encourage smuggling.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.50</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 4  
Monetary Policy 4		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 4  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  Country Reports on Economic Policy and Trade Practices, U.S. Senate Report No. 103-68, 
Washington, D.C., February 1994.
</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
</HTML>



