<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>El Salvador</TITLE>
<H2>EL SALVADOR</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Central American country of El Salvador suffered a terrible civil war in the 1970s and 
1980s. After peace was established in 1991, the economy slowly began to recover. Despite massive 
infusions of foreign aid, El Salvador's economy grew an average of only 2 percent per year from 
1982 to 1989. Once it began to make market reforms, however, its economy began to grow 3.4 
percent in GDP in 1990, 3.5 percent in 1991, 4.8 percent in 1992, and 5 percent in 1993. Under 
President Alfredo Cristiani, the government relinquished control of prices, slashed import tariffs, 
privatized most of the financial system, and followed a relatively tight monetary policy. While some 
problems remain, El Salvador's economy is growing and showing signs of increasing prosperity.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
As a member of the Central American Common Market, a group of nations committed to 
lowering trade barriers, El Salvador has agreed to reduce its tariffs. Tariffs generally range 
from 5 percent to 20 percent, with some minor exceptions. Moreover, El Salvador adds a 7 
percent tax on imports, and some individual states may impose special tariffs for up to 30 
days. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   This brings El Salvador's average tariff rate to 
above 10 percent. Another burden for importers is a government requirement for a health 
certificate for imported poultry. Since this certificate is nearly impossible to get from the 
government, poultry imports are effectively banned. El Salvador also maintains tariffs on 
corn, rice, and sorghum and soybean meal. When the price for these imported products 
falls below a certain level, a 20 percent tariff is added.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 2.5-Stable (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR>
El Salvador has a top marginal income tax rate of 30 percent. The tax rate for the average 
income level is zero percent. El Salvador's top corporate income tax rate is 25 percent. El 
Salvador has a 10 percent value-added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
El Salvador's government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 10.6 percent, down from 14 
percent in 1980.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of inflation)</I><BR>
El Salvador had an average annual inflation rate of 17.4 percent from 1980 to 1991. That figure 
went down to 11.2 percent in 1992 but rose again to 19 percent in 1993.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Foreign investors can invest in almost any enterprise except electricity and telecommunications, 
which remain in government hands. El Salvador provides tax incentives for some 
investments. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Foreign banks are permitted to operate in El Salvador as if they were domestic banks. All 
restrictions on foreign banks in El Salvador have been removed. Most local and foreign 
banks are allowed to compete in a wide range of financial services. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
The government has eliminated price controls on some 240 goods. However, price controls 
remain on bus fares, petroleum products, and utilities. El Salvador has a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
The government of El Salvador has undertaken a massive privatization program. It is returning 
banks and hotels, for example, to the private sector. Expropriation, however, is still 
possible. Although private property is guaranteed by law, the country lacks efficient legal 
protection of property.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation)</I><BR>
Since price controls have been abolished, the government maintains little regulatory control over 
most businesses. The exception is agriculture, which is highly regulated. Businesses must 
prepare an environmental impact statement every time they wish to expand. Moreover, the 
government requires 11 days of paid vacation a year, an annual 30 percent bonus after only 
15 days of work, and a Christmas bonus equal to 12.5 days' pay. These and other 
regulations pose a moderate burden on business.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Some labor, such as construction, is still provided by the black market. In addition, restrictions 
on agricultural products have produced a black market for such goods as poultry. 
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.85</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 2  
Taxation 2.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>



<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  El Salvador's government receipts from taxes on international trade equaled about 6 percent of 
imports in 1992. This figure does not include additional taxes on trade that raise the average tariff rate to 
above 10 percent.
</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
<BR>
</BODY>
