<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>France</TITLE>
<H2>FRANCE</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	France is the fourth-largest industrialized economy in the world. Like much of  Europe, 
France's economy has been in a recession for the past several years. While essentially a free 
market, France has a history of centralized administrative control over parts of the economy.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of protectionism)</I><BR>
As part of the European Union, France's trade policy is the same as other EU members. 
Imports are subject to the common EU external tariff of 3.6 percent. While economic 
integration has reduced some trade barriers, it has raised others. Particular industries 
affected by raised barriers are electronics, telecommunications equipment, medical and 
veterinary equipment, and agricultural products.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable  (High tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
France has a top income tax rate of 30.5 percent. The tax rate on the average income is 15 
percent. France's complicated tax structure puts the total corporate tax paid over 35 
percent. In addition, France maintains an 18 percent to 33 percent capital gains tax, an 18.6 
percent value-added tax, a business activity tax of up to 20 percent, and a social 
contributions tax of 16 percent to 45 percent.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Total government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 18.6 percent.  The French 
government has monopoly control over several parts of the economy, such as energy 
generation and supply, rail transportation, postal services, telecommunications, and tobacco 
production and distribution. Moreover, many state-owned companies dominate various 
industrial sectors, skewing pricing and adding inefficiency to the entire French economy. 
Some of these companies are in such industries as iron and steel, aluminum, coal mining, 
aerospace, nuclear energy, and many forms of transportation except trucking. France is 
undergoing a limited privatization program and for this reason receives an improving score. 
Despite some of its problems, the level of government intervention in the economy is low 
by global standards. 
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of inflation)</I><BR>
France had an annual inflation rate of 5.7 percent from 1980 to 1991. Today, it remains around 
2 percent to 3 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Non-French investors must receive approval from the Ministry of Economics before buying a 
French business. The Ministry of Economics can block any investment if it deems the sale 
as violating the "national interest."
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
The French government controls two of France's largest banks, Banque Nationale de Paris and 
Credit Lyonnais. This control severely reduces the availability of credit.  Nevertheless, 
foreign investors are finding it easier to invest in French financial services and to open 
banks.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
France has a long history of legalized monopolies in such areas of the economy as 
telecommunications, public infrastructure, electricity, and rail transportation. In 1987, 
however, the French government removed price controls, and most prices are now set by 
the market. Products still under price controls are pharmaceuticals, books, tobacco, 
agricultural products, coal, and steel. France maintains a minimum wage, and some wages 
are controlled by the government.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Property rights are uniform throughout France. Enforcement is adequate. However, there are 
some impediments to acquiring property. The French Constitution, for example, states that 
any company defined as a national public service or as a natural monopoly must pass into 
state ownership. The Constitution allows the state to nationalize companies that fall into this 
category. However, in practice and by global standards, protection is high.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of regulation)</I><BR>
The reforms established by the EU have made opening a business in France easier. Obtaining a 
business license is relatively easy, but some hurdles still must be overcome. For example, a 
company must obtain a registration number from the district commercial court. To do so, a 
copy of the business's lease, plus other documentation, must accompany the application. 
However, France has made some progress in streamlining this cumbersome registration 
process by incorporating all the registration requirements into one office.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low black market activity)</I><BR>
The French black market is conducted mainly in gambling and in the buying and selling of 
illegal weapons, drugs, and stolen merchandise.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.30</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 3  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 1		Regulation 2  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 1  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
