<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Ghana</TITLE>
<H2>GHANA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The West African country of Ghana gained independence from Great Britain in 1957. 
Prime Minister Kwame Nkrumah quickly transformed Ghana into a one-party socialist state. This 
lasted until 1992 when Flight Lt. J.J. Rawlings legalized political parties. Rawlings won Ghana's 
1992 presidential elections, though their fairness has been questioned. An economic liberalization 
program begun by Rawlings in 1983 has improved what was a collapsing socialist economy. Annual 
growth has averaged 4.5 percent since then, giving Ghana one of Africa's best-performing 
economies. Ghana benefits from a relatively well-developed infrastructure and rich raw materials.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">

 <P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Ghana's average tariff rate is a high 26.9 percent. And while most goods do not require 
licenses, handling and customs delays are frequent. 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR>
Ghana has a progressive income tax system with a top bracket of 35 percent. The average 
taxpayer falls within the 5 percent bracket. Ghana taxes corporate profits at a top rate of 45 
percent. In addition, Ghana has a 5 percent capital gains tax and a gift tax that ranges from 
zero percent to 15 percent. 
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
The government consumes 9.4 percent of the GDP. State-owned enterprises dominate many 
industrial sectors, including the petroleum, steel, diamond, timber marketing, retail, and 
construction industries.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of inflation)</I><BR>
Ghana's average rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 was 40 percent. Inflation was 14 percent 
for 1993. 
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
The government developed a new investment code in 1992 that eased restrictions on private 
sector investment. Some investment incentives exist, including exemptions from import 
duties on specified products. One free trade zone exists at the port of Tema. Despite these 
liberalizing measures, restrictions on foreign investment remain in several sectors. An 
inefficient and corrupt bureaucracy stipulates the nature of investments, including the 
amount and source of capital, the nationality and number of shareholders, and training 
requirements for Ghanaian labor. Moreover, prospective investors are screened on a case-
by-case basis, among other conditions. Full foreign ownership is permitted only for projects 
that bring foreign currency into the country.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Seven commercial banks operate over 200 branches throughout Ghana. Interest rate controls 
have been abolished by the central bank, which otherwise maintains tight control over 
financial activities. There is a government monopoly on personal insurance. Several state-
owned banks are being divested from government control. Ghana's central bank enjoys no 
political independence.   
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Employers and workers generally are encouraged to negotiate wages and working conditions. 
There is a minimum wage. Most price controls have been eliminated.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
The investment code guarantees private property against expropriation, which remains unlikely. 
However, domestically owned property is less secure than property obtained through 
foreign investment. There have been instances in the last several years of arbitrary seizure 
of domestic commercial properties.   
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
Private sector investors face a burdensome licensing process. Foreign firms face regulations that 
force them to hire local employees. Businesses face other problems, such as the need to 
gain bureaucratic approval for acquiring and selling land.   
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of black market activity)</I><BR>
The dismantling of price controls has reduced the number of Ghana's once-legion "economic 
criminals" and removed a large incentive to engage in black market activity.   
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.30</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 4		Black Market 2  
   
  </PRE>


