<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Greece</TITLE>
<H2>GREECE</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Greece won independence from the Ottoman Empire in 1827, establishing a monarchy in 
1833. Germany invaded Greece in 1941 and occupied it until 1944. Communists backed by the 
Soviet Union attempted to take over Greece in 1946. This led to a civil war in which many lives 
were lost. Greece emerged from the civil war as a Western democracy and joined the North 
Atlantic Treaty Organization in 1952. It has been involved in a bitter stand-off with Turkey over the 
island of Cyprus, which both countries claim as their own. Since joining the European Community 
in 1981, Greece has worked to bring its economy in line with the other democracies of Europe. 
Four years of free market economic reforms undertaken by the conservative government of Prime 
Minister Constantine Mitsotakis came to an end in October 1993 when Mitsotakis lost his reelection 
bid to Andreas Papandreou, the Socialist leader who was Prime Minister from 1981 to 1989.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Greece has a low average tariff rate of 3.6 percent. As a member of the EU, it must conform to 
EU trade standards and practices.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR>
Greece has a top income tax rate of 40 percent. The rate that applies to the average income 
level is 5 percent. Greece has a top corporate income tax of 35 percent. Greece also has a 
35 percent capital gains tax and an 18 percent value-added tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 19.7 percent and falling. However, state-
owned industries make up a significant portion of the economy.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of inflation)</I><BR>
Greece had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 17.7 percent. Inflation has 
decreased to nearly 15 percent since 1992.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
 Greece has an open foreign investment code which invites many investments. However, there 
are some restrictions on foreign ownership, especially in banks, which prevent 100 percent 
foreign ownership. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Greece prevents non-EU members from owning more than 40 percent of state-owned banks. 
The government still owns a significant number of banks.   
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Some prices are set by the government, including those for bread, freight charges, motor 
vehicle insurance, pharmaceuticals, and telephone service.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (High level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Chances of property expropriation in Greece are unlikely. Property receives adequate protection 
from the courts.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of regulation)</I><BR>
Greece is highly bureaucratic, and many government regulations pose a burden on business.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Greece is a popular place for smugglers, especially in recorded music and videos.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 2.80</TH>  
    
Trade 2				Banking 4  
Taxation 3			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 2  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 2		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
