<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Guatemala</TITLE>
<H2>GUATEMALA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The Central American country of Guatemala gained independence from Spain in 1821. 
Afterwards the country underwent decades of civil unrest and war. In 1985, a democratically 
elected government began to reform the economy by reducing the state role in the economy. The 
process has faltered in the 1990s, leaving the country with a reform-resistant legislature. However, 
in the chaos, the private sector has managed to flourish. The government sector accounts for only 
12 percent of GDP. 
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Like El Salvador and Costa Rica, Guatemala imposes tariffs on most products at rates from 5 
percent to 20 percent. However, tariffs are much higher on some selected items, and a 7 
percent tax is added to all imports above the top tariff rate. Guatemala had an average tariff 
rate in 1992 of 16.3 percent. Today, non-tariff barriers exist in the form of import licensing 
requirements for many agricultural products. Tariffs in 1992 rose to 20 percent on corn and 
30 percent on rice. Guatemala has a trade quota on the import of poultry. 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 2.5-Stable (Moderate tax rates)</I><BR>
Guatemala has a top tax rate of 25 percent. The tax rate that applies to the average income level 
is 15 percent. Guatemala has a top corporate income tax of 25 percent. Guatemala also has 
a 15 percent capital gains tax, a 7 percent value-added tax, and a land tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low government consumption)</I><BR>
Guatemala's government consumes 5.9 percent of the country's GDP.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of inflation)</I><BR>
Guatemala had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 15.9 percent. Today, it 
remains about the same.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Foreign investment in Guatemala is relatively welcome, although restrictions are imposed on 
foreign investment in utilities and in such domestic industries as fishing, mining, and 
forestry. Moreover, the inefficient and confusing licensing process prevents some 
investments in banks, auditing, and insurance.  
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
The government does not permit full foreign participation in Guatemala's banking industry. 
Domestic banks remain tightly regulated by the government and the central bank. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Guatemala has a minimum wage law. Guatemala has no official price controls, but the 
government heavily influences prices through massive subsidies.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Property is subject to expropriation in Guatemala. There is little legal protection of property in 
the court system. Corruption is present. However, private property is legal.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
Guatemala's regulations are ambiguous, leaving their interpretation up to capricious government 
bureaucrats who apply them arbitrarily. Since the bureaucracy is corrupt, businessmen 
often resort to bribes to escape oppressive regulations. The Guatemalan government forces 
businesses to provide 15 days of paid leave and other bonuses and benefits. Businesses are 
severely burdened by these and other regulations.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of black market activity)</I><BR>
A rather large black market exists in American-made tape and compact disc recordings, videos, 
televisions, and electronic goods.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.05</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 2.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 3		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 3  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
