<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Guinea</TITLE>
<H2>GUINEA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The West African country of Guinea was colonized by France in 1891. It became 
independent of France in 1958.  After independence, the government took over control of the 
economy and established a socialist state. With plentiful natural resources, Guinea could have 
benefited from a free market. Instead, its state-controlled economy stagnated. In 1990, a new 
constitution was adopted, allowing for limited political and economic reforms.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism) </I><BR>
Guinea has an average tariff rate of about 17 percent. This includes a uniform tariff rate of 15 
percent, plus a varying tariff rate from 20 percent to 40 percent on luxury items. Licenses 
are required for all imported goods. In addition, a pre-shipment inspection is required by 
customs. These licenses and inspections may pose a barrier to some imports.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates) <BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4.5-Stable (Very high tax rates) </I><BR>
Guinea has a top income tax rate of 40 percent. The amount that applies to the average income 
level is 25 percent. It has a top corporate tax rate of 35 percent. Guinea also has a 35 
percent capital gains tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of government consumption) </I><BR>
Guinea's government consumes 8.4 percent of GDP. It has attempted to decrease its swollen 
government by planning to privatize schools and return doctors to the private sector by 
ending the state-supplied health care system. Yet it still has a large state-owned sector.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of inflation) </I><BR>
Guinea had an average annual inflation rate from 1988 to 1992 of 23.9 percent. In 1993, 
inflation was reduced to 18 percent. It was about the same for 1994.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate barriers to foreign investment) </I><BR>
Guinea has been opening its economy to foreign investment since 1990. It has adopted an 
investment code based on a system used by the Ivory Coast which allows investments in 
many industrial sectors. Nevertheless, foreign investments remain at risk because of crime, 
an inefficient bureaucracy, and corruption.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low restrictions on banking) </I><BR>
There are few restrictions on banks. Most are in private hands following a massive privatization 
of the banking industry in the late 1980s and early 1990s. Foreign banks are welcome. Yet 
many people complain that credit is too tight and interest rates are too high. 
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of wage and price controls) </I><BR>
Price controls have been removed on most items, but they still remain on some foodstuffs. 
Although there is no minimum wage, the government may implement one soon.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property) </I><BR>
Property is not completely secure in Guinea. Government corruption, an inefficient judiciary, 
and poor law enforcement prevent the full legal protection of property. Crime remains a 
threat to property.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3- (Moderate level of regulation) </I><BR>
Although the government has taken steps to remove government interference in private 
business, a huge bureaucracy remains an impediment to free enterprise. Moreover, the 
government has plans to introduce a new set of labor and health standards for business that 
could stifle the creation of new businesses.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of black market activity) </I><BR>
Guinea has a large black market, especially in luxury goods that face a 40 percent tariff rate.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.35</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 2  
Taxation 4.5			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 4		Regulation 3  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
