<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Guyana</TITLE>
<H2>GUYANA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	The South American country of Guyana won its independence from the United Kingdom in 
1966. Since then, the country has followed mainly a socialist economic course. Guyana is among 
the poorest countries in the world. The government is controlled by the People's Progressive Party, 
which won the election in 1992. Guyana's past economic policies have seriously impeded economic 
growth. However, since 1992, the government has made sweeping reforms aimed at attracting 
foreign investment by relying on the free market.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Despite easing formal barriers to trade, Guyana's tariffs remain high. Moreover, government 
paperwork, corruption, and informal obstacles provide substantial barriers to trade. Import 
licenses are required for fruit, meat, and poultry. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT> 
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 4-Stable (High tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 4-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
Guyana has a flat tax of 33.3 percent of income. Guyana has a top corporate tax rate of 45 
percent. Guyana also has a 20 percent capital gains tax and a property tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Guyana's central government consumes about 15 percent of the GDP. State-owned companies 
account for as much as 40 percent of total production.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of inflation)</I><BR>
Guyana's average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 was 35 percent. No information was 
available for later years.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
There are few restrictions on foreign investment in Guyana. However, investors are concerned 
over civil unrest, crime, and corruption. Foreign investors complain of lengthy delays in 
government approval.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Guyana's banking system is not very competitive. It has five commercial banks, three of which 
are either partly or wholly owned by the government. The government severely restricts the 
availability of credit. Most banks do not provide credit, but simply offer basic banking 
services.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Guyana maintains a minimum wage. Price controls exist on electricity rates.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
After privatizing the communications, fishing, rice, and timber industries, the government has 
slowed privatization. Political opposition to privatization has been growing. Expropriation of 
private property, therefore, remains a threat.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
Some sectors like utilities and other state-owned industries are highly regulated. Corruption 
often hinders the ability of companies to do business in these areas that are highly regulated 
by the state.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Guyana has a rather large black market. In some cases, consumers are forced to steal electricity 
because of the inefficiently run government utilities. These illegal connections are 
performed by black market electricians. Black markets also exist in labor, transportation, 
and a host of other services.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.70</TH>  
    
Trade 4				Banking 4  
Taxation 4			Wage and Prices 2  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 5		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>


<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  The average tariff rate was not available.

</FONT>

