<HTML>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Hong Kong</TITLE>
<H2>HONG KONG</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	Hong Kong is a colony of the United Kingdom until 1997, at which time it will become a 
province of the People's Republic of China. In the meantime, attempts are underway by Britain and 
the Hong Kong government to solidify democracy and maintain Hong Kong's vast market 
economy. Hong Kong now is one of the most economically free countries on earth. The 
government does not interfere in the marketplace, taxes are low and predictable, government 
spending increases are closely linked to economic growth. Foreign trade is free, regulations are 
transparent, and regulations are applied uniformly and consistently.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Hong Kong levies no import tariffs. There are, in fact, very few barriers to imports in Hong 
Kong, which is one of the most accessible markets in the world.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 2-Stable (Low tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 1-Stable (Very low tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 1.5-Stable (Low tax rates)</I><BR>
Hong Kong's top marginal personal income tax rate is capped at 15 percent. The tax on the 
average income level is 2 percent. Hong Kong's corporate tax is a flat rate of 17.5 percent.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Hong Kong's government consumption is about 8 percent of GDP.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2+ (Low level of inflation)</I><BR>
Hong Kong's inflation rate has averaged 7.5 percent since 1980.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
The government of Hong Kong encourages foreign investment. The government provides tax 
holidays for many investments. These include donations of land to foreign businesses, 
accommodating infrastructure policies, and even education services.
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Hong Kong is a world banking center. It is one of the most stable banking environments in the 
world. Banks are completely independent of the government. However, local banks tend to 
form cartels that have erected barriers to the formation of new banks.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Wages and prices are set completely by the free market. The government has the power to 
enforce "minimum wages," but it has never done so.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very high level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Private property rights in Hong Kong are completely protected. The legal system to protect 
those rights is highly efficient and effective.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of regulation)</I><BR>
Hong Kong has a simple business licensing system. There are few regulations imposed on 
businesses. Regulations are not a burden to business, and they are applied uniformly.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 1-Stable (Very low level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Since little is illegal in Hong Kong, its black market is negligible. 
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 1.25</TH>  
    
Trade 1				Banking 2  
Taxation 1.5			Wage and Prices 1  
Government Consumption 1 	Property Rights 1  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 1  
Foreign Investment 1		Black Market 1  
   
  </PRE>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
