<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>India</TITLE>
<H2>INDIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	 India gained independence from Britain in 1947 and became a republic in 1950. For much 
of the following three decades, India pursued socialist economic policies, nationalizing industries, 
raising trade tariffs, subsidizing industries, and raising taxes. India's economy suffered as a result. 
However, India began to liberalize its economy in 1991, accepting foreign investment, and reducing 
barriers to trade. As a result, India's economy has been growing.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">

<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5+ (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
India had an average tariff rate of over 40 percent in 1992. In addition, India maintains non-
tariff barriers in a number of ways. For example, the government requires import licenses 
for such products as agricultural goods and pharmaceuticals. India has an outright import 
ban on some products, such as some textiles and clothing.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 5-Stable (Very high tax rates)</I><BR>
India's top income tax level is 52 percent. The tax on the average income level is about 20 
percent. India has a top corporate tax rate of 50 percent. India also maintains a 20 percent 
capital gains tax and interest and sales taxes.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of government consumption)</I><BR>
India's government consumes 20.1 percent of GDP. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>
   State-owned enterprises account for most of the GDP.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2- (Low level of inflation)</I><BR>
India had an average annual inflation rate from 1980 to 1991 of 8.2 percent. Inflation reached 
10.1 percent in 1992.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Foreign investors cannot have 100 percent ownership of an Indian concern without government 
approval. Stock ownership is limited to 51 percent in many cases. Moreover, India's high 
trade tariffs stifle investments because businesses cannot import foreign components to 
manufacture their products. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4+ (High level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Most Indian banks are government-owned. Only three U.S. banks operate in India with plans 
for a fourth. These banks are under heavy government regulation. While plans exist to be 
more open to foreign banks, the banking market in India remains heavily regulated and 
government-controlled.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3+ (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
India maintains price controls on many items. In addition, the state subsidizes government-
owned enterprises, which has the effect of subsidizing prices. India has a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
The massive gap between rich and poor leads to government policies that redistribute wealth, 
mainly through direct property expropriation. While India has an efficient court system, 
property remains at risk in rural areas from crime and corruption.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
India's economy is heavily regulated. The large public sector must meet all kinds of 
requirements in order to remain open for business, including restrictive licensing 
requirements and many more. These regulations are a heavy burden for the business 
sector. Some corruption remains present.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity)</I><BR>
India's huge tariffs make smuggling foreign goods into the country a very profitable business. 
India has a rather large black market, mostly in foreign goods.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.70</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 4  
Taxation 5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 3 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This figure was generated by taking India's central government expenditure as a percentage of 
GDP in 1991, the most recent year available. This probably understates government consumption.

</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#169 1995 The Heritage Foundation
