<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<TITLE>Indonesia</TITLE>
<H2>INDONESIA</H2>
<HR SIZE=2>

<P>	An archipelago between Australia and Malaysia, Indonesia gained independence from the 
Netherlands in 1949. Afterwards, Indonesia moved toward authoritarianism and socialism. Little 
progress has been made to integrate Indonesia's economy into the developed world. Massive 
infusions of foreign aid have been squandered, and little economic progress has resulted. Indonesia, 
however, recently has pursued some reform.
<P><IMG SRC="alb.gif">
<P><B>Factor #1: Trade Policy</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of protectionism)</I><BR>
Indonesia has an average tariff rate of 20 percent. <FONT SIZE="-2">[1]</FONT>   There 
are quantitative import restrictions on a number of products, including wheat and soybeans. 
Some local content requirements apply to automobiles, auto parts, and dairy products. 
Automobiles not assembled in Indonesia are assessed a 100 percent tariff.
<P><B>Factor #2: Taxation</B><BR>
<I>Score - Income taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Score - Corporate taxation: 3-Stable (Moderate tax rates)<BR>
Final Taxation Score: 3.5-Stable (High tax rates)</I><BR>
Indonesia has a top income tax rate of 35 percent. The average income level is taxed at 15 
percent. Indonesia has a top corporate income tax rate of 35 percent. Indonesia also has a 
35 percent capital gains tax, a 10 percent value-added tax, and a sales tax.
<P><B>Factor #3: Government Consumption of Economic Output</B><BR>
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of government consumption)</I><BR>
Indonesia's government consumption as a percentage of GDP is 17.1 percent.
<P><B>Factor #4: Monetary Policy</B><BR>  
<I>Score: 2-Stable (Low level of inflation)</I><BR>
Indonesia had an average annual rate of inflation from 1980 to 1991 of 8.5 percent. In 1993, 
inflation was 10.2 percent.
<P><B>Factor #5: Capital Flows and Foreign Investment</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate barriers to foreign investment)</I><BR>
Indonesia does not generally treat foreign businesses the same as domestic businesses. The 
Indonesian President must personally approve every foreign investment project. Foreign 
direct investment is not permitted in 34 areas, including retail trade, radio and broadcasting, 
and domestic transportation. Foreigners can own no more than 49 percent of an Indonesian 
company. 
<P><B>Factor #6: Banking</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of restrictions on banking)</I><BR>
Up until the late 1980s, no foreign banks had been granted a license since 1969. Some changes 
have occurred to allow more foreign bank participation, but foreign banks are still highly 
regulated. In many cases, foreign banks can only operate through a joint venture with an 
Indonesian bank. Domestic banks are also highly regulated and controlled by the 
government.
<P><B>Factor #7: Wage and Price Controls</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of wage and price controls)</I><BR>
Most prices are set by the market. However, price controls exist on many products, including 
pharmaceuticals. Indonesia has a minimum wage.
<P><B>Factor #8: Property Rights</B><BR>
<I>Score: 3-Stable (Moderate level of protection of private property)</I><BR>
Expropriation of property is possible. Indonesia's legal framework is based on outdated Dutch 
Commercial Codes that have not been updated since colonial times. Court rulings can be 
arbitrary and inconsistent.
<P><B>Factor #9: Regulation</B><BR>
<I>Score: 4-Stable (High level of regulation)</I><BR>
Indonesia's regulatory environment is characterized by bribery, kickbacks, and corruption. 
Many regulations are applied arbitrarily, and bribes may be necessary to receive an 
"exemption" from a government regulation.
<P><B>Factor #10: Black Market</B><BR>
<I>Score: 5-Stable (Very high level of black market activity)</I><BR>
Indonesia has a very large black market, mainly because of its high level of trade protection.
<P><B>Summary</B><BR>
 
<P>
<P>
























<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>
Overall Ratings			Overall Score 3.35</TH>  
    
Trade 5				Banking 3  
Taxation 3.5			Wage and Prices 3  
Government Consumption 2 	Property Rights 3  
Monetary Policy 2		Regulation 4  
Foreign Investment 3		Black Market 5  
   
  </PRE>


<FONT SIZE="-1">
<P><B>Endnotes</B>
<P>[1]  This is a simple average of actual rates. See "Foreign Trade Barriers," United States Trade 
Representative's Office, Washington, D.C., 1994.
</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>
